text:
Except for the penalty kicks, watching the play as a French was a much more epic experience. Where this mostly argentina supporting crowd only stood with uncertainty and tense, what we got was one of the most epic comeback, the hope, the burst of emotions at each goal of Mbappé. The emotions were so deep that for a week, I was genuinely convinced that France won. 
Still proud to this day of what my national football team made of this final: from a boring and hard to watch first period, to this legendary drama, that I hope will last for decades in people's memories.

text:
The World Cup had a viewership of 5.6 billion in total (no, I'm not making that up, look it up), and the final was watched by over 2 billion people. And yet, the US still wants to treat football aka "soccer" like some irrelevant sport. Yes, 329 million Americans vs 5.6 billion in the rest of the world. And right now, they're already hyping their Superbowl again as "the biggest sports event in the world", when in reality, it only averages a viewership of 100 million each year. F**king clowns that are the US media and their fake news, as usual.
Only one sport rules the world, and it isn't even just a sport. Football is CULTURE in the vast majority of the world.

text:
It's laughable that not a single person here acknowledges the obvious rule book infringement—no fewer than 7 French players brazenly storm onto the pitch while the ball remains in play. Such a contravention is without question, a punishable offence, warranting a free kick for the opposing side.
Were the culprits in question Argentina, the outcry would be deafening, with cries of "rigged" echoing relentlessly through these very comments. But, of course, the narrative shifts when the team in question happens to be one graced by Messi’s presence, yeah? 😂😂

text:
Nos puden decir que somos exagerados, que como vamos a llorar, que como nos vamos a poner asi......
Pero ese momento, ese segundo en el que vez la pelota entrar fue magico, fue fue abrazarte con tu niño interior y repararlo a ese niño argentino que cada vez que agarraba una pelota soñaba con salir campeon del mundo pero que la vida lo llevaba por otro rumbo....
Ese segundo fue olviarte de todo por un rato, las peleas, el dinero, el trabajo, la bandera politica o de que fueras, porque si, fuimos muchos los que nunca habiamos visto a la seleccion ganar un mundial...
Fue el sentirnos mejores por un rato, abrazarnos con los nuestros y con cualquier desconocido por la calle, abrazarte a la distancia con los que estaban lejos y abrazarte con los que ya no estan y deseando que bajaran 10 minutos para darle un abrazo de campeon, porque si, quien no tiene a ese abuelito, abuelita, tio, hermano, padre, madre que soñaba con esto pero se fueron antes......
Dejamos mucho en el futbol??? Si
Dejamos que la seleccion nos maneje el humor?? Si 
Pero nada nos quita que por un segundo nos olvidamos de todo para juntos sentirnos los mejores por un rato..... Gracias Argentina

text:
I didn't watch any of  Argentina matches. I wanted them to win since the beginning. I didn't watch any of them cause my blood pressure could go high but mostly cause i watched all of Messi's world cup matches on previous worldcups and they lost. So for good luck matters I decided not to watch.

During the game I was driving to my grandma's, when I was a block away the streets were so silent I thought Argentina had lost the game, so I asked: Who won? A man said Argentina won. And I replied: Why are you sad?

It seems they were cheering for France.

I got really happy and nervous. Messi deserved that long time ago.

author: @memoriesforlife903

text:
I am from Romania. The first world cup final i saw an TV was the one who took place in 1986, when Maradona won the title. I saw the final as a kid with 10 other neighbors also kids, my father and my uncle. Everybody in the room wanted Argentina to win, my father and my uncle... West Germany. When the germans made 2 -2 all the kids were sad and the adults were happy. But later 3 - 2 for Argentina, and the room was on fire, all the kids were super happy, just like in this clip.
In 2014 i was so mad because Argentina lost to Germany and i saw praying to see Messi at least once rising the world cup. In 2018 was not possible but in 2022 my dream came true.
I watched the final with some friend, an argentinian who lives now in Romania and my father. This time we were all Argentinians fans. The best football final i have ever see, with best ending.
Messi and Argentina deserved it.
Now i am really glad they won again Copa America, and really expecting to see the next World Cup in USA.
Gob bless Messi and Argentina for the joy they brought.

text: 나는 한국사람이지만 36년간 이 순간을 기다려왔다. 카니지아, 바티스투타, 크레스포, 오르테가, 테베즈, 사무엘, 아이마르, 시메오네, 베론, 콜로치니, 리켈메, 사비올라, 디알레산드로, 마스체라노, 이구아인, 아구에로.. 숱한 선수들의 기억이 스쳐 지나간다. 특히 2002년 바티스투타의 눈물은 아직도 잊을 수 없다. 나도 같이 울었다. 비록 한국이 4강에 갔지만 기쁨보다는 슬픔이 더 컸던 대회였다. 영어가 미국,영국만의 언어가 아니듯이 아르헨티나 축구팀을 응원하는 사람들은 아르헨티나인 4천만정도가 아니고 전 세계적으로 최소 40억 명 이상의 사람들이 있다는 사실을 알아주었으면 좋겠다. 좀 더 욕심을 내고 싶지만 아쉽게도,  다음 2026년 대회에서 우승을 포기하려는 아르헨티나 팬들이 많이 있다. 현재 피파랭킹1위라지만 더이상 강팀이랑 경기하지 않고 순위를 지키려고만 하는거 같다. 메시와 디마리아가 은퇴하면 가망이 없는것은 사실이다. 하지만 기량이 쇄퇴하더라도 메시와 디마리아, 오타멘디가 다음대회에도 계속 뛰어야만 한다고 생각한다. 그들의 기량은 2022대회때보다 1단계 이상 하락했겠지만... 알바레즈, 엔조, 데폴, 맥알리스터, 가르나초의 기량이 1단계 이상 상승하고 있다. 디발라, 라우타로, 에밀리아노의 능력은 올라가지는 않고 있지만 내려가지도 않고 있다. 난 모든 선수들의 소속팀 경기를 대부분 챙겨보며 실력을 체크하고 있다. 이들과 함께 다시 뛴다면 다음 대회를 통해 가슴의 별 4개가 불가능하지는 않다는 결론을 얻게 되었다.

text:
Estallo el pais con el gol de Montiel, despues un silencio (fue cuando todos lloramos con tanta congoja) y la gente comenzo a salir a la calle. Era risas, abrazos y llorar, asi sucesivamente. Hasta hoy sigo llorando de esa misma manera cada vez que veo estas imágenes. Desde el día cero sabia que el 2022 nuestra selección se consagraba Campeón del Mundo y lo afirme cuando perdió contra Arabia, tenía una seguridad absoluta. Sucedio y todos los argentinos fuimos felices al unisono. Vamos Argentina, Carajo!! Te amo Patria querida!!! 🇦🇷❤️⭐⭐⭐💪🏻
La selección, el país, la gente nos merecemos esta felicidad, veniamos de la pandemia de perder y perder seres queridos,vecinos,amigos, de la lucha diaria que tenemos a nosotros nada nos ha sido fácil y siempre seguimos adelante con tantas fuerzas, el mundial me encanta porque en esa época nos tratamos tan amables, nos saludamos sin conocernos.Necesitabamos esta gran caricia al alma y de paso como nunca en diciembre, en las fiestas la tristeza de los que no estaran en la mesa,el cansancio de un año de trabajo, el estres. Realmente nos lleno de energías, mas de la que mostramos al mundo, a pesar de todo somos incansables🤭🫂🤗
Además darnos cuenta que del otro lado del mundo, nos conocían y nos querían. Que todos se sorprendieran como somos cuando para nosotros es natural somos pura pasión en todo los ámbitos de la vida, para nosotros lo importante es la patria,la familia y la amistad, dirán el fútbol, si! Pero es en el deporte que flamee nuestra bandera.

text:
For most people, something like this can only happen once in their whole life. And I'm eternally grateful to experience this live on TV. 

It's one of the most beautiful thing that ever happened in my life. The idea of Lionel Messi, the greatest there ever was, to have the World Cup to finally complete his football can only written by God.

That's why I heavily disagree with the proposal of making World Cup once every two years, instead of four. This moment can only happen _precisely_ because it only happen once every four years. And to have someone like Messi and the whole Argentina football team win it in this fashion can only happen once in many hundreds of years. 

It's simply that magical of a moment. I would never trade this memory with however much riches there are in the world.
author: @YosepRA

text: I still remember where I was when this happened. I was working the dairy section of Publix and I wasn’t allowed to have my phone during shop hours. Needless to say, I hid my phone in my apron and remember pulling my phone out to watch the shootout. When Montiel scored that goal…… I knew I was getting yelled at by my manager but I screamed so loud that Argentina won and so did 4 other guys in that store. We all got together and celebrated like crazy, until others joined in more and more. Suffice to say, this game is too beautiful

text: On behalf of all Arabs and Qataris, I apologize for any negative events that led to the World Cup. But please understand that some of the stats are over exaggerated. Like consuming beer. It’s still allowed but only in clubs or areas designated around the stadium (which is the same as any western country honestly lol). Or woman’s rights. Please ask any Qatari woman you know and ask her if she is oppressed in ANY way. We spoil our women more then any other people and if you really know an Arab family you know as well they treat daughters like princesses. And as for the LQBTQ rights, even though the Qatari government already welcomed any and all sexes regardless of what they identify as, 8 of the 32 host nations who have hosted the World Cup also ban homosexuality. If Qatar is being bashed for this it’s only right to bash the other host nations as well, not pick and choose.  And Yes, there was deaths but the ones that were directly linked to building the stadiums are 37. In Russia and Brazil for the world cups the numbers were pretty similar (give or take 5). The other 6500 migrants who died mainly died of heat strokes, road side accidents, and many other causes that were OUTSIDE the work place. That’s like my friend coming to work on the 2026 World Cup in America and he gets killed in a hit and run while he is outside for the night away from work. Should that be counted as a “migrant death due to building the stadiums for the USA?” With that being said again i sincerely apologize for anything and everything that we were accused of and we are honored to host the great nations of the world. It’s good to have everyone together after these past two years of lock down. So please let’s stop bashing an entire people and country and focus on the happiness

text:
Sad really. Those complaining and those victimising are both hypocrites. Europe can't call out Qatar on their wrong doings because they're the pot in this pot-kettle exchange. The Human Rights Association only call out abuse (mostly) if it garners the kind of attention they want. Europe and several parts of the world are as corrupt as Fifa & Qatar supposedly. LGBTQ+ is quite sensitive to talk about, since everyone keeps getting offended by the truth these days...but I believe, if the society you find yourself in frowns upon something, especially if it's tied to their religious belief, just shut your mouth and play ball. It's not as though you're moving there permanently...if it bothers you so much you want to call them out and waste everyone's time, you could as well sit back home where your sexual identity is tolerated, so everyone can have their piece of mind. It's not right to force your opinion or beliefs on others, especially in an already established islamic system, who have sent clear warnings in their rules.

This World Cup certainly is going to be a pain in the arse, for all the wrong reasons. Can't wait till it's all over!
But Justice is needed though! For all the lives lost! ✌🏽

text: Rigged isn't the right word, and you shouldn't only take this match to claim such things. But look at the whole tournament. We have to be honest here; Argentina did get more decisions in their favor than other teams. Was it rigged? No, but it could have been influenced. Take Qatar; how did they get the World Cup in the first place? We all know how... so would it be that strange if they tried to "push" Argentina for the win? Especially if you knew beforehand it would probably be Messi's last chance to win it. The thing with football is, it's not a sport with clear-cut rules.  A lot of times, it's how the referee and VAR interpret the situation. So, sadly, football, in my eyes, will never be a completely fair sport. We have all seen really shady decisions that left us with irritated feelings, or however you react to them. Not even talking about Argentina alone, but about the sport as a whole. Anyway, do I think it was rigged? No, but I wouldn't be surprised if they tried to push for Argentina to win.

text:
A game being rigged is like influencing the odds, in other words, influencing the people evaluating how to pass mistakes. To a strong team like Argentina, that is like a almost guarantee that they can just bypass rules and regulations. Similar for the last Spain EC. Somehow for specific groups there are just rule bending priviliges. Not always, but in some games it is extremely noticeable. Yes, football is rigged, and Fifa is ultra famous for being corrupt. Why would anyone even defend something else?

Saying that people need proof for this just shows that you do not understand how football business and general law works. Even more, most of the comments here are also probably by children understanding very little about the actual dynamics. 

Again, the cup being rigged means: there is influence on how mistakes are being evaluated, either by referee bias or by corruption. This influences the game, given that a team is good, also maximizes the chances of winning. Not sure why people here get it wrong

text:
My friend,for someone who loves and follows Football,at least for the last 20 years,knows very well that Messi ( and  Barcelona)has been FIFA and UEFA "Protégé.
It's a fact of life, because there are no such thing as coincidences.
Argentina has the new World Cup Record,for the team with more penalties awarded,5 penalties in 7 games.
If Messi was awarded with the 2nd yellow card,most likely wouldn't be present on the final.
And many other "small" details, that put together can make all the difference between winning or  being the "other" team.
PS: why did Messi won other Ballon D'or in 2023...???!!
Because he won the 2022 World Cup...??!!
Because if winning a World Cup it's enough to be awarded with the Ballon D'or,i can say the name of 3 Argentina players who also Won the same World Cup,who did had a much more Successfull  season than Lionel Messi.
Not to mention other players,from other countries that were also more ( by far) Successfull than Messi on the same season,but didin't won a world Cup.
I'am a 63 years old Die Hard Football Fan,and always try to be FAIR ,even when concerning my Beloved National Team,and my Beloved "personal" Team .
Always try to see the Football as an Honest and Fair game, where the best is the one that Deserves to Win.
Unfortunably, because of some Greedy, Dishonest and Immoral people, Football also have been Corrupted to the core.
Even with those 2 POS criminals, Blatter and Platini out of the picture,the seeds of Corruption that those 2 Leeches planted on FIFA and UEFA,are still growing Strong and in some cases in a Disgusting Shameless way.
Unfortunably, since players started to be "Bought" by dozens an hundreds of Millions €, Football nowadays it's another huge Profitable business,than the Real and Greatest Sport on Earth.

1)
سُبْحَا نَ اللهِ وَ بِحَمْدِهِ عَدَدَخَلْقِهِ، وَرِضَا نَفْسِهِ، وَزِنَةَ عَرْشِهِ وَمِدَادَ كَلِمَاتِهِ.
 Subhanallahi wa bihamdihi, ai’dada khalqihi, wa ridhaa nafsihi, wa zinata ‘ar shihi, wa midaada kalimaatihi.

2)


رَضِيتُ باللَّهِ رَبًّا، وَبِالْإِسْلَامِ دِيناً، وَبِمُحَمَّدٍ صَلَى اللَّهُ عَلِيهِ وَسَلَّمَ نَبِيَّاً

Reward: Allah has promised that anyone who says every morning or evening will be pleased on the Day of Resurrection.


3)
SubhanAllah
سُبْحَانَ الله
Reward: say 100 times a day and 1,000 Hasanah will be written for you or 1,000 sins will be wiped away.

سُبْحَانَ اللهِ الْعَظِيمِ وَ بِحَمْدِ هِ

لَا إِلٰهَ إِلَّا اللَّهُ وَحْدَهُ لَا شَرِيكَ لَهُ، لَهُ الْمُلْكُ وَلَهُ الحَمْدُ وَهُوَ عَلَى كُلِّ شَيْءٍ قَدِيرٌ

8)
أَعُوذُ بِكَلِمَاتِ اللَّهِ التَّامَّاتِ مِنْ شَرِّ مَا خَلَقَ

10)
بِسْمِ اللَّهِ الَّذِي لَا يَضُرُّ مَعَ اسْمِهِ شَيْءٌ فِي الَْأرْضِ وَلَا فِي السَّمَاءِ وَهُوَ السَّمِيعُ الْعَلِيمُ

text: Ahead of the tournament I predicted that a win by a South American country would be strongly favored by FIFA, with Argentina being the best candidate not having won the cup since 86. Just look at the history of the WC and you will see how the number of trophies were balanced between South American and European teams up until 2002 when it wast the last time a South American team, in that case Brazil, won. Since then, 2006, 2010, 2014 and 2018 editions were all won by European teams and a fifth consecutive one would probably not be welcome. Of course any team would win the trophy but the way Argentina did it somewhat confirms my previous suspicions.

text:
For those who dont’t know the actual rules
- Kicking a ball in to the bench isn’t a red card, it’s a yellow card offense at best and very rarely does it end up in red cards


- messi’s handball in the game vs the netherlands isn’t a yellow card, bc Messi did not prevent a goal or promising attack, as it was a handball in the middle of the pitch with the rest of his team behind him on their own half, and no promising attack or shot on goal was in motion!


- the penalty vs poland was a penalty, bc even though the ball was already gone, remember lloris hit danilo and portugal got a penalty in the group stage of the euros! If that is a penalty for excessive force used, then so is the one vs messi! Which also raises the question, should neuer have gotten red in 2014? A german ref back then believed so!
In any case, the foul by lloris set a precedent for keepers using excessive force. 


- The penalty vs the netherlands was a clear and obvious foul by dumfries, as he swiped the foot of acuna!
This can be seen from multiple angles and is not up for debate. 

Fun fact: the equalizing goal from the netherlands never should’ve happened, as the free kick it came from came after a foul where an argentinian player was pushed by a dutch player. Therefore the foul should’ve gone to argentina and they most likely would’ve won 2-1


- Any claims from the dutch that the argentinians were super aggressive is hilarious and the irony in their claims couldn’t be more… ironic😂 as they are the only nation associated with more games that got out of hand than anybody else, they even hold the record for games with most  cards, multiple games!
Especially ironic since vvd could’ve been sent off and timber should’ve been sent off with red cards themselves and even more ironic as the head coach v gaal hired a sports mentality coach who instructed the players on how to get under the skin of their opponents, how to annoy them and how to irritate them during the game and the penalty shoot out! We saw this happen and dumfries and weghorst were reprimanded. 

- The penalty vs france was a penalty, as dembele hits the foot of di maria not once but twice!
First he hits the ankle on the outside causing di maria to trip, then he pushes him in the back and his foot swipes away di marias foot on the inside!
This also can be seen from multiple angles and even the british media pointed it out (alan shearer during the half time), and again, whether you think it’s a soft penalty or not isn’t relevant, as there is no such thing as hard or soft penalties, a pen is a pen

- The argument the french media used of argentinian bench players being over the sideline during play is also useless as the french bench did the same and the rules clearly state that play won’t be stopped unless it directly interferes with play and it wont be stopped until the ball is out of play or stopped for a foul etc. 

- The penalty vs croatia is also a clear penalty as once again the rules are clear in this, the keeper made no real attempt to stop the ball and only made his body big to block his opponent! Thereby taking away an opportunity for alvarez to finish the tap in!
Alvarez did not run into the keeper as some people try to claim, as the keeper stretched out his body wau to fast and too close to alvarez, for it to be reasonable to expect alvarez to move out of the way!

Keepers missing the ball and catching a player also usually always end up in penalties. So once again there is precedent

If pundits and commentators had more knowledge of the rules, they would be able to inform the public better and then there would be no claims of rigged world cups for messi. 


Side note, morocco was better, portugal just got beaten fair and square.

text: As someone who has spent 20 years living and working with the world's most excluded and at risk communities I can't praise this video enough,  such an important piece of work. The SA and Brazil world cups led to Governments burning slums and displacing or worse thousands of residents to build stadiums and roads that were worthless afterwards and wasted fortunes, then Russia,  now Qatar.. Its decades now since a World Cup you could watch with a clear conscience. Mainstream media seemed to think one sentence about the issues in Qatar and then an "on with the game" attitude was OK but I'm so pleased to see someone stick their neck out and say NO,  its not OK.  With all the research and subject knowledge to back it up. Been a fan of the channel for awhile and enjoy all the content but this is another level for me,  so pleased you made this video 🙏

- In Qatar it's not punishable to be gay, it's punishable to engage in gay sexual intercourse.
- Some laws like women who need guardians might sound absurd to you but they are matters which should be respected, if you hear people's take on it there you might change your mind.

text:
Yawn... corruption?  Maybe.  It certainly would be in keeping with the history of FIFA and the World Cup and frankly I'm sure that it will continue for many years to come.  What I find most interesting is that every time a nation outside of Western Europe is chosen, the W. European and particularly the English media go on attack.  Most recently they relentlessly bad-mouthed the following using every racist or regional prejudice and stereotype imaginable to ward off fans and discredit those nations... 
1) South Africa '10 - wont possibly be ready in time, visitors are in serious danger of being raped/attacked/killed, corruption, corruption, blah blah
2) Brazil  '14 - wont possibly be ready in time, visitors are in serious danger of being raped/attacked/killed, corruption, corruption, blah blah. oh and your kidneys or other vital organs will be stolen.
3) Russia '18 - Boycott Putin, Russian football hooligans are a deadly threat to everyone to the point of many Europeans actually believing it and not showing to support their teams (meanwhile Mexico, African nations and other western hemisphere nations were there in full force), corruption, corruption, blah blah.
As it turned out they were not the disasters predicted and those nations put on fantastic world cups.  Until Germany '06 the WC had been held in W. Europe at least every other cycle. Prior to '94, Mexico was the only exception outside of W. Europe or South America.  What has impressed me most however is that over the past 30 yrs or so FIFA has waved off Western Europe's bullying and held the world cup in nations/regions never or rarely held before  - the US, S. Korea/Japan, S. Africa, Russia and now Qatar. This for me has contributed tremendously to the growth and spread of the beautiful game globally.  That's the way its supposed to be.

text:
What a small brained way to look at things and quite frankly, the need to point the finger to feel superior is beyond nauseating. Yes, literally not one country is worthy of holding a World Cup. I will ignore your ridiculous commentary, but I will say; don't worry Alfie, you can get as much BBC as you want just do be a neon sign telling everyone that is what you want. 
But to speak about what is way more important for something that will happen, whether you like it or you don't. The logistics of Qatar are extremely concerning because it is such a small country and everything is in Metropolitan Doha. So, what is going to have to happen is help from their neighbors; Bahrain, UAE, and Saudi Arabia. Logging will be tough but the 3 neighbors have enough to make it work, I'm not sure if Oman will try to lend their hand as much as the other 3. Bahrain, Abu Dhabi, and Dubai will have more than 10 flights a day. Dammam I'm sure will also increase their flights but not as many. Also boat rides will be introduced to connect the neighbors with Qatar. The details are still being worked on but I like the idea. 
For football fans who aren't interested in going to recreate Thailand in the desert, you will have plenty of things to do all throughout the Gulf; hiking, sand dune riding, sky diving, scuba diving and snorkeling and many cultural things that are very interesting. Though if you just can't help yourself and debauchery is your way of life, Bahrain is the place for you, yet it is the smallest of the GCC countries so I am sure their Logging is being filled as I write this comment. If you are going to go, the cheapest route will probably be to stay at a hotel in Eastern Province (Metropolitan Dammam), Saudi Arabia and fly into Doha on match day. I am interested in one of the boat trips. As of now I'm still waiting to see if I have won a chance to buy tickets. 
Finally, why did I waste my time writing this comment? It's the World Cup, try to enjoy the festival of football. The Arabs are wonderful, hospitable people. Going into it with such negativity means you won't even give yourself the opportunity to be pleasantly surprised and it just might be best that you stay home.

text:
Sports should be apolitical. Yes, that means that even shitty dictatorships should be able to host. OR it should only be hosted be countries with an impeccable human rights and freedoms record.
Complaining about Qatar 2022 is such a weak ass argument, when much worse countries have hosted the WC and Olympics. And much worse countries continue to participate and win glory for themselves.
So which is it? Apolitical or based on human rights record? Until then, this smacks wholly of convenient hypocrisy (which is the largest Western export at this point)

text:
You didn't even touch on one of the worst human rights abuses, probably to avoid being falsely accused of "islamphobia".  People in predominantly islamic countries are forced (under threat of "legal" punishment) to obey islamic law.  This includes NOT eating or drinking during the day in the month or ramalamadingdong...I mean, "ramadan".  

No food or water.  While doing extreme manual labour.  In 50C temperatures.

As for countries, you didn't mention the slave labour from North Korea.  The Kim regime sent people there and profited from enslaved people who at best got nothing and went home worn out, or worse suffered crippling injuries or died.  How many, from a regime that view its citizens as disposable meat?

27:30 - Finland engages in eugenics, REQUIRING the sterilization allowing Transgender people in order to change documentation.   So yeah, not perfect.

28:30 - Defence of "religion = culture = law" was the justification for what England did to Ireland's catholics, Germany did to jews, and Israel is doing now to Palestinians.

33:00 - We know from history that banning South Africa from rugby tours did more to end apartheid than "participating will encourage reform!" ever did.  See also: the Commonwealth Games excluding or banning countries.  Regimes want to participate to glorify themselves, kicking them out sends them a message.

33:40 - What will happen if people display flags or shirts in human rights colours or signs?  Russia and China both got REALLY pi$$y about this one.

35:30 - I love the last line.  "Fence sitting."
